  "issue_number": 2433,
  "issue_title": "Implement `responseType: 'text|json'` using `TextDecoderStream`",
  "issue_body": "#### What problem are you trying to solve?\n\nWhen a HTTP response is big (e.g. >100MB), once it has been fully downloaded, Got converts it to a string (unless `responseType: 'buffer'` is used):\n\nhttps://github.com/sindresorhus/got/blob/de19b463b1875847f955a53d2f5b0a539ed0ded3/source/core/response.ts#L144-L150\n\n`buffer.toString()` is synchronous and can take several seconds to complete if buffer is very large. \n\nThis sudden CPU-bound bottleneck at the end of an HTTP request can be quite noticeable, especially when using the `downloadProgress` feature, since the completion is reported as 100% _before_ the response body has been parsed. This makes it look like the request freezes after \"100%\" completion.\n\n...\n\n#### Describe the feature\n\nUsers can work around this right way by using `got.stream()`. However it would be a simpler and better experience for Got to automatically parse the body incrementally instead.\n\nThat is, instead of using `buffer.toString()`, implement body parsing with [`TextDecoderStream`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/TextDecoderStream), decoding each new chunk as they come.\n\n...\n\n#### Checklist\n\n- [x] I have read the documentation and made sure this feature doesn't already exist.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-02-23T10:14:32Z",
